## Investigation

### Email Analysis

Multiple employees at SwiftSpend Financial reported receiving suspicious emails. Some users had already submitted credentials and were no longer able to access their accounts.

The investigation began by reviewing the provided phishing email samples to identify recipients, sender information, attachments, and embedded links.

The email related to a quote for services rendered was received by:

```text
[redacted employee]
```

The adversary used the following sender address to deliver the phishing emails:

```text
Accounts.Payable@groupmarketingonline.icu
```

This sender address was treated as an indicator of compromise.

---

### Phishing URL Analysis

The attachment sent to one of the employees contained a redirection URL.

The root domain identified from the redirection URL was:

```text
kennaroads.buzz
```

When the phishing URL was opened in the lab browser, it displayed a fake login page impersonating:

```text
Microsoft
```

The page attempted to mimic a Microsoft sign-in portal in order to collect user credentials.

---

### Exposed Directory Review

Further investigation of the phishing domain showed that directory listing was enabled.

The exposed directory reviewed was:

```text
/data
```

The directory contained an exposed phishing kit archive:

```text
Update365.zip
```

This indicated that the attacker had left phishing kit files accessible on the web server.

---

### Phishing Kit Hash Analysis

The phishing kit archive was downloaded into the lab environment and hashed using the `sha256sum` command.

```bash
sha256sum Update365.zip
```

The SHA256 hash of the archive was:

```text
ba3c15267393419eb08c7b2652b8b6b39b406ef300ae8a18fee4d16b19ac9686
```

The hash was then investigated using VirusTotal.

VirusTotal identified the archive as malicious, with detections associated with phishing and Trojan activity.

The additional threat category identified was:

```text
Trojan
```

The VirusTotal details showed that the archive contained:

```text
49 files
```

---

### Captured Credential Log Review

The exposed phishing kit directory contained a log file showing submitted credentials.

The investigation confirmed that at least one internal user submitted credentials more than once. For responsible reporting, the affected user email and submitted passwords have been redacted.

```text
Repeated credential submission: [redacted internal user]
Submitted passwords: [redacted]
```

This finding indicated that the phishing page was actively collecting credentials and that at least one user may have been compromised.

---

### Phishing Kit Source Code Review

The phishing kit archive was extracted and the `submit.php` file was reviewed.

The source code revealed the email address used by the adversary to collect stolen credentials:

```text
m3npat@yandex.com
```

This email address was treated as an additional indicator of compromise.

---

### Encoded File Review

The phishing URL also exposed a `flag.txt` file. The content was decoded using CyberChef.

For responsible reporting and to avoid publishing TryHackMe challenge answers, the decoded value has been redacted.

```text
Decoded value: [redacted TryHackMe flag]
```

