## Conclusion

This investigation identified a phishing campaign targeting SwiftSpend Financial employees with a fake Microsoft login page.

The adversary used the sender address `Accounts.Payable@groupmarketingonline.icu` and hosted phishing content on `kennaroads.buzz`. Further investigation revealed an exposed `/data` directory containing the phishing kit archive `Update365.zip`.

The archive hash was investigated using VirusTotal and was associated with phishing and Trojan activity. The phishing kit also contained exposed credential logs and a `submit.php` file configured to send harvested credentials to `m3npat@yandex.com`.

Victim emails, submitted passwords, and the TryHackMe flag were redacted from this report to follow responsible cybersecurity reporting practices.

This project demonstrates a practical SOC analyst workflow for phishing investigation, including email analysis, phishing URL review, threat intelligence enrichment, credential exposure analysis, phishing kit review, and incident response documentation.

